    {
      "id": 1,
      "text": "Key Colony Beach grew from the former Shelter Key island, originally a low‑lying sandy island before 1950s dredging.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1,
        5,
        6
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key_Colony_Beach%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The city’s only road, the Sadowski Causeway, links it to U.S. 1 and was named after the developer who reclaimed the island.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        10,
        6
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key_Colony_Beach%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "At the south end of the causeway, West Ocean Drive opens to Sunset Park, a small waterfront park with a fountain and gazebo.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        12,
        13
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key_Colony_Beach%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "East Ocean Drive’s numbered streets run east‑west toward Shelter Bay, and the Key Colony Beach Motel and Club sit along its most notable stretch.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        14,
        15
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key_Colony_Beach%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "The city’s tropical savanna climate borders a monsoon climate, giving it a Caribbean‑like weather pattern unique to the Florida Keys.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        18,
        20
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key_Colony_Beach%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "The Sadowski Causeway’s dockside restaurant, Sparky’s Landing, still serves charter fishing boats and locals.",
